{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17632815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17632815"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:44:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:44:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17443"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17443","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17443"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10133"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70920"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10133"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17443"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56387"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5331"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23733"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23832"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70920"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESocial norms play a crucial role in shaping public health behaviours and outcomes. These unwritten rules guide how people act within their communities and social groups.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the difference between descriptive and injunctive social norms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Descriptive norms are written rules, while injunctive norms are unwritten rules","Descriptive norms apply to groups, while injunctive norms apply to individuals","Descriptive norms are culture-specific, while injunctive norms are universal","Descriptive norms are stable, while injunctive norms change frequently","Descriptive norms are what people actually do, while injunctive norms are what people ought to do"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe key distinction is that \u003Cstrong\u003Edescriptive norms reflect what people actually do in practice, while injunctive norms reflect what people ought to do\u003C/strong\u003E according to social or moral standards. For example, a descriptive norm might be that most people eat fast food weekly, while the injunctive norm might be that people should eat a healthy, balanced diet.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWritten versus unwritten rules\u003C/strong\u003E: both descriptive and injunctive norms are typically unwritten social expectations that emerge through social interaction rather than formal documentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGroup versus individual application\u003C/strong\u003E: both types of norms operate at both individual and group levels, influencing behaviour across different social contexts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECulture-specific versus universal norms\u003C/strong\u003E: both descriptive and injunctive norms vary between cultures and societies, reflecting local values and practices.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStable versus changing norms\u003C/strong\u003E: both types of norms can evolve over time as societies change and new behaviours become accepted or expected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these different types of social norms is crucial for public health interventions, as they can target either what people currently do (descriptive norms) or what they believe they should do (injunctive norms) to promote behaviour change.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Social norms are informal rules and expectations that guide behaviour within a society or group.","Descriptive norms reflect what people actually do, while injunctive norms reflect what people ought to do.","Social norms can significantly influence health behaviours and public health outcomes."],"references":["Dempsey RC, McAlaney J, Bewick BM. A Critical Appraisal of the Social Norms Approach as an Interventional Strategy for Health-Related Behavior and Attitude Change. Front Psychol. 2018;9:2180. Published 2018 Nov 6. doi:10.3389/fpsyg.2018.02180","Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56387"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17443"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56387"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T15:17:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T15:18:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10133"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70920"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"